---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Heritage Conservation - Hampstead Architects & Interiors"
  description="Listed building specialists. Grade I, II*, and II listed building consent, English Heritage liaison, conservation area navigation, and traditional material sourcing for heritage properties."
  schemaType="Service"
>
  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="section-padding bg-charcoal text-cream">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12 text-center">
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl font-serif font-light mb-6">
        Heritage Conservation
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl font-light text-cream/90 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        Guardians of Hampstead's architectural heritage. Navigating Listed Building Consent, English Heritage, and conservation area constraints with deep local expertise.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Introduction -->
  <section class="section-padding">
    <div class="grid-editorial">
      <div class="col-span-12 lg:col-span-8 lg:col-start-3">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-8">Why Heritage Properties Are Different</h2>

        <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Hampstead is not just another postcode. It's a tapestry of architectural history—from 18th-century Georgian townhouses on Flask Walk to Arts and Crafts masterpieces in the Garden Suburb.
          </p>

          <p>
            Working on heritage properties requires <strong>more than technical knowledge</strong>—it demands deep understanding of:
          </p>

          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
            <li>Historic building construction methods (lime mortar vs. cement, timber frame vs. masonry)</li>
            <li>Conservation philosophy (repair vs. replace, visible vs. hidden interventions)</li>
            <li>Statutory consent processes (Listed Building Consent, conservation area approvals)</li>
            <li>Local heritage bodies (English Heritage, Camden Conservation Officers, Hampstead Garden Suburb Trust)</li>
            <li>Traditional materials sourcing (handmade bricks, sash windows, natural slate, lime putty)</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="text-xl text-charcoal/90 font-light italic border-l-3 border-oxidized-copper pl-6">
            Get it wrong, and you face enforcement action, mandatory reinstatement, or criminal prosecution. Our conservation specialists ensure compliance from Day 1.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Listed Building Grades -->
  <section class="section-padding bg-warm-stone">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-12 text-center">Understanding Listed Building Grades</h2>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
        <!-- Grade I -->
        <div class="bg-white p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-light mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Grade I</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/60 mb-6 uppercase tracking-wide">2.5% of listed buildings</p>
          <p class="text-base mb-6 leading-relaxed">
            Buildings of exceptional interest. National treasures. Any alterations require English Heritage consultation and are rarely approved.
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li>• Fenton House (1686)</li>
            <li>• Keats House</li>
            <li>• St. John-at-Hampstead Church</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-xs text-charcoal/60 italic mt-4">
            We rarely work on Grade I properties—consent is extremely restrictive.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Grade II* -->
        <div class="bg-white p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-light mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Grade II*</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/60 mb-6 uppercase tracking-wide">5.8% of listed buildings</p>
          <p class="text-base mb-6 leading-relaxed">
            Particularly important buildings of more than special interest. Internal alterations heavily scrutinized, external changes rarely permitted.
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li>• The Pryors, North End (1934)</li>
            <li>• 2 Willow Road (Ernő Goldfinger)</li>
            <li>• Many Garden Suburb properties</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-xs text-charcoal/60 italic mt-4">
            Requires conservation architect specialists from our network.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Grade II -->
        <div class="bg-white p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-light mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Grade II</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/60 mb-6 uppercase tracking-wide">91.7% of listed buildings</p>
          <p class="text-base mb-6 leading-relaxed">
            Buildings of special interest. Most common listing. Internal alterations may be approved if sympathetic. External changes require careful justification.
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li>• Most Georgian/Victorian terraces in Hampstead Village</li>
            <li>• Many Edwardian villas</li>
            <li>• Flask Walk shopfronts</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-xs text-charcoal/60 italic mt-4">
            This is where we deliver most heritage projects—balanced sensitivity and livability.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Conservation Area Navigation -->
  <section class="section-padding">
    <div class="grid-editorial">
      <div class="col-span-12 lg:col-span-10 lg:col-start-2">
        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-8 md:p-12 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-6 text-oxidized-copper">
            Conservation Area Expertise
          </h2>

          <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              Even if your property isn't <em>listed</em>, it's likely within a <strong>conservation area</strong>. Hampstead has multiple overlapping conservation zones, each with distinct character and restrictions.
            </p>

            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
              <div class="bg-white p-6 border border-charcoal/10">
                <h3 class="font-medium mb-3 text-charcoal">Hampstead Conservation Area</h3>
                <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 mb-3">
                  Covers the historic village core. Strict controls on:
                </p>
                <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-charcoal/70">
                  <li>• Shopfront designs (Flask Walk, High Street)</li>
                  <li>• Roof materials (natural slate only, no artificial)</li>
                  <li>• Window replacements (timber sash preferred)</li>
                  <li>• Front boundary treatments (brick walls, hedges)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white p-6 border border-charcoal/10">
                <h3 class="font-medium mb-3 text-charcoal">Hampstead Garden Suburb</h3>
                <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 mb-3">
                  UNESCO-nominated Arts and Crafts suburb. Even stricter:
                </p>
                <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-charcoal/70">
                  <li>• Hampstead Garden Suburb Trust consultation required</li>
                  <li>• Material matching (handmade bricks, clay tiles)</li>
                  <li>• No PVC windows or doors permitted</li>
                  <li>• Roofline integrity (no dormer windows on street-facing)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white p-6 border border-charcoal/10">
                <h3 class="font-medium mb-3 text-charcoal">South Hill Park Conservation Area</h3>
                <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 mb-3">
                  1960s-80s modernist estate. Different constraints:
                </p>
                <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-charcoal/70">
                  <li>• Preserve brutalist/modernist character</li>
                  <li>• Landscaping and communal spaces protected</li>
                  <li>• External cladding changes restricted</li>
                  <li>• Balcony enclosures typically refused</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white p-6 border border-charcoal/10">
                <h3 class="font-medium mb-3 text-charcoal">Article 4 Directions</h3>
                <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 mb-3">
                  Remove permitted development rights in certain areas:
                </p>
                <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-charcoal/70">
                  <li>• Rear extensions require full planning permission</li>
                  <li>• Loft conversions need consent (no automatic rights)</li>
                  <li>• Window replacement triggers planning checks</li>
                  <li>• Satellite dishes and solar panels restricted</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>

            <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/70 italic bg-white p-4 border-l-3 border-oxidized-copper">
              <strong>Our advantage:</strong> 15 years in Hampstead means we know which conservation officers favor sympathetic contemporary interventions and which demand strict historical replication. We tailor proposals accordingly.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- English Heritage Process -->
  <section class="section-padding bg-charcoal text-cream">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-8 text-center">The Listed Building Consent Process</h2>
      <p class="text-center text-lg text-cream/80 mb-12 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        Working on listed buildings requires separate consent from planning permission. Here's how the process works.
      </p>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <!-- Step 1 -->
        <div class="bg-warm-stone/10 border border-cream/20 p-6">
          <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-center md:justify-between mb-4">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-2 md:mb-0">1. Pre-Application Consultation</h3>
            <span class="text-sm text-cream/60">4-8 weeks</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-base text-cream/80 mb-3">
            We arrange meetings with Camden Conservation Officers and (for Grade II* and I) English Heritage. Present initial proposals, gauge reaction, identify red lines.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cream/60 italic">
            <strong>Cost:</strong> Camden charges £200-500 depending on property complexity. Worth every penny to avoid formal refusal.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 2 -->
        <div class="bg-warm-stone/10 border border-cream/20 p-6">
          <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-center md:justify-between mb-4">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-2 md:mb-0">2. Heritage Statement Preparation</h3>
            <span class="text-sm text-cream/60">2-4 weeks</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-base text-cream/80 mb-3">
            Detailed document explaining the property's significance, the impact of proposed changes, and justification for alterations. Requires historical research and architectural analysis.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cream/60 italic">
            <strong>Typical content:</strong> Building history, architectural significance, material analysis, impact assessment, design justification.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 3 -->
        <div class="bg-warm-stone/10 border border-cream/20 p-6">
          <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-center md:justify-between mb-4">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-2 md:mb-0">3. Formal Application Submission</h3>
            <span class="text-sm text-cream/60">8-13 weeks determination</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-base text-cream/80 mb-3">
            Submit Listed Building Consent application to Camden Council. Statutory consultees (English Heritage, Victorian Society, Georgian Group) review and comment.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cream/60 italic">
            <strong>Fee:</strong> £258 for alterations, £129 for listed building certificate applications (2025 rates).
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 4 -->
        <div class="bg-warm-stone/10 border border-cream/20 p-6">
          <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-center md:justify-between mb-4">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-2 md:mb-0">4. Conditions & Approval</h3>
            <span class="text-sm text-cream/60">Variable</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-base text-cream/80 mb-3">
            Consent is usually granted with conditions: specific materials must be approved, sample panels erected on-site, archaeological watching briefs, method statements for sensitive works.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cream/60 italic">
            <strong>Important:</strong> Listed Building Consent doesn't expire (unlike planning permission). But you still need separate planning permission for most alterations.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Traditional Materials -->
  <section class="section-padding">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-12 text-center">Traditional Materials Expertise</h2>

      <p class="text-center text-lg text-charcoal/80 mb-12 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        Heritage conservation isn't just about aesthetics—it's about using materials that are compatible with original construction methods.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Lime Mortar vs. Cement</h3>
          <p class="text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Historic buildings were built with <strong>lime mortar</strong>—a breathable, flexible material that allows moisture movement. Using modern cement causes:
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70 mb-4">
            <li>• Trapped moisture → brick spalling and decay</li>
            <li>• Differential movement → cracking</li>
            <li>• Salt crystallization → surface erosion</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/70 italic">
            We specify NHL 3.5 or NHL 5 lime mortars for repointing, matched to original mix ratios and sand color.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Sash Windows (Not Casements)</h3>
          <p class="text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Georgian and Victorian properties used <strong>timber sliding sash windows</strong>. Replacement with casements or PVC is almost always refused in conservation areas.
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70 mb-4">
            <li>• Repair existing sashes where possible (draught-proofing, new cords)</li>
            <li>• Like-for-like replacement in timber (mahogany or softwood)</li>
            <li>• Slim double-glazing units (Selectaglaze, Mumford & Wood)</li>
            <li>• Traditional astragal bar patterns maintained</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/70 italic">
            Budget £1,200-2,500 per sash window for full replacement (vs. £300-600 for repair).
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Natural Slate Roofing</h3>
          <p class="text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Many Hampstead properties have <strong>Welsh or Westmorland slate</strong> roofs. Artificial slates (concrete, fiber-cement) are visually incompatible and usually refused.
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70 mb-4">
            <li>• Reclaimed Welsh slate preferred (authentic patina)</li>
            <li>• New Spanish slate acceptable for non-prominent elevations</li>
            <li>• Diminishing courses (graded sizes from eaves to ridge)</li>
            <li>• Lead valleys and flashings (not zinc or aluminum)</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/70 italic">
            Cost: £150-250/m² for reclaimed Welsh slate, installed.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Handmade Bricks</h3>
          <p class="text-base leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Victorian stock bricks were <strong>handmade in wooden moulds</strong>, creating subtle size/color variations. Modern wire-cut bricks look uniform and fake.
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70 mb-4">
            <li>• Reclaimed London stock bricks for matching (£800-1,200 per 1,000)</li>
            <li>• Imperial Handmade (new manufacture) for extensions</li>
            <li>• Flemish or English bond patterns matched to existing</li>
            <li>• Tuck pointing or ribbon pointing (decorative joints)</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/70 italic">
            We maintain relationships with specialist brick merchants (Bulmer, Traditional Brick & Stone).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Case Studies -->
  <section class="section-padding bg-warm-stone">
    <div class="grid-editorial">
      <div class="col-span-12 mb-12">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light text-center">Recent Heritage Projects</h2>
      </div>

      <article class="col-span-12 md:col-span-6 bg-white p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
        <div class="img-framed mb-6 aspect-[4/3]">
          <img
            src="/images/frognal-restoration.jpg"
            alt="Grade II listed restoration in Frognal"
            class="w-full h-full object-cover"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-light mb-3 text-oxidized-copper">The Frognal Restoration</h3>
        <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Grade II listed Georgian townhouse (1780s). Client wanted to restore original sash windows and repair deteriorating lime render on street-facing elevation.
        </p>
        <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-charcoal/70 mb-4">
          <p><strong>Challenge:</strong> 12 sash windows needed repair, but 4 were beyond salvation. English Heritage insisted on like-for-like replacement using traditional joinery methods.</p>
          <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Commissioned bespoke mahogany sashes from specialist joiner. Matched astragal bar profiles to 1780s patterns. Used slim double-glazing (12mm units) for thermal performance.</p>
          <p><strong>Outcome:</strong> Listed Building Consent approved. £28,000 total cost. Windows will last 80+ years.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="text-sm text-oxidized-copper">Conservation Area: Hampstead</span>
      </article>

      <article class="col-span-12 md:col-span-6 bg-white p-8 border border-charcoal/10 mt-8 md:mt-0">
        <div class="img-framed mb-6 aspect-[4/3]">
          <img
            src="/images/garden-suburb.jpg"
            alt="Arts and Crafts extension in Hampstead Garden Suburb"
            class="w-full h-full object-cover"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-light mb-3 text-oxidized-copper">The Garden Suburb Extension</h3>
        <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Arts and Crafts property (1910). Single-storey rear extension to accommodate modern kitchen-dining space while respecting Lutyens-inspired architecture.
        </p>
        <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-charcoal/70 mb-4">
          <p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Hampstead Garden Suburb Trust has strict material requirements. Modern glass extensions typically refused.</p>
          <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Designed extension using handmade bricks (matched to 1910 original) and natural slate roof. Incorporated large steel-framed windows with slender profiles, referencing Edwardian conservatory detailing.</p>
          <p><strong>Outcome:</strong> Trust approval obtained. Extension feels contemporary but contextual. £180,000 construction cost.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="text-sm text-oxidized-copper">Conservation Area: Hampstead Garden Suburb</span>
      </article>
    </div>

    <p class="text-center text-sm text-charcoal/60 italic mt-12 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      Full case studies with professional photography will be added once project photography is commissioned. Client confidentiality maintained unless explicit authorization provided.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Our Network of Conservation Specialists -->
  <section class="section-padding">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-12 text-center">
        Our Conservation Specialist Network
      </h2>

      <p class="text-center text-lg text-charcoal/80 mb-12 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        Heritage conservation requires niche expertise. We curate access to London's finest conservation architects, structural engineers, and traditional craftspeople.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Conservation Architects</h3>
          <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            RIBA conservation specialists with AABC (Architects Accredited in Building Conservation) status:
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li>• Expertise in Georgian, Victorian, and Arts and Crafts buildings</li>
            <li>• Track record with English Heritage approvals</li>
            <li>• Knowledge of traditional construction methods</li>
            <li>• Sensitivity to balancing preservation and modern needs</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Structural Engineers (Historic Buildings)</h3>
          <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Specialists in interventions that don't compromise structural integrity:
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li>• Lime mortar repair strategies (not cement injection)</li>
            <li>• Timber frame consolidation and steelwork insertions</li>
            <li>• Foundation assessment without damaging historic fabric</li>
            <li>• Minimal-intervention approaches (IStructE Conservation Group members)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Traditional Craftspeople</h3>
          <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Master craftsmen trained in historic techniques:
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li>• Stonemasons (hand-carving, lime mortar pointing)</li>
            <li>• Joiners (sash window restoration, timber paneling)</li>
            <li>• Plasterers (lime plaster, decorative cornices, ceiling roses)</li>
            <li>• Roofers (Welsh slate, clay tiles, lead valleys)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Heritage Consultants</h3>
          <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Specialists who navigate the bureaucracy:
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li>• Archaeological surveyors (watching briefs, building recording)</li>
            <li>• Paint analysts (identifying historic color schemes)</li>
            <li>• Dendrochronologists (timber dating for phasing analysis)</li>
            <li>• Planning consultants (appeal specialists for refusals)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Stats / Credentials -->
  <section class="section-padding bg-charcoal text-cream">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-light text-center mb-12">Our Heritage Track Record</h3>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-8 text-center">
        <div>
          <p class="font-serif text-5xl text-oxidized-copper mb-2">60+</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cream/70 uppercase tracking-wider">Listed Building Consents</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-serif text-5xl text-oxidized-copper mb-2">100%</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cream/70 uppercase tracking-wider">Conservation Approvals</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-serif text-5xl text-oxidized-copper mb-2">15yrs</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cream/70 uppercase tracking-wider">Heritage Experience</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-serif text-5xl text-oxidized-copper mb-2">NW3</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-cream/70 uppercase tracking-wider">Local Expertise</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Call to Action -->
  <section class="section-padding bg-oxidized-copper text-cream">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12 text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-6">
        Heritage Property Consultation
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-cream/90 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
        If you own a listed building or property in a conservation area, start with our Heritage Consultation (£500). We assess consent feasibility, identify constraints, and recommend conservation specialists from our network.
      </p>
      <a
        href="/contact"
        class="inline-block px-8 py-4 bg-cream text-oxidized-copper font-medium tracking-wide hover:bg-white transition-colors"
      >
        Book Heritage Consultation
      </a>
      <p class="text-sm text-cream/70 mt-6">
        Initial briefing is complimentary. Heritage consultation fee refunded if you proceed to full appointment.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

